  <h3>Test</h3>

  <p>We tested our prototype with 5 people initially, their jobs and industries varied, but all of them had
    high-competency with technology.</p>

  <h3>Results</h3>

  <p>We analysed all of the sessions by making notes and then met to perform affinity mapping exercises to help
    summarise the issues. In short the first prototype did a good job, but needed some improvements:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>The prototype was simple, there are lots of edge-cases especially for data that are not accounted for.</li>
    <li>Can/should we unbundle some elements, while still focusing on the USP?</li>
    <li>Iterate on the terminology used e.g. “Data Operations”</li>
    <li>Iterate on the review process</li>
    <li>Iterate on the spreadsheet creation process</li>
    <li>Iterate on the “export” creation process.</li>
    <li>Potentially explore a solution for mapping that can work for both types of data operation.</li>
    <li>Explore importing data for new customers</li>
    <li>Explore permissions and how they will inform the structure of the application</li>
  </ul>

  <p>We then recommended some ideas for next steps under the broader goals of defining an MVP through further research
    and prototype iteration:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>Fill in the gaps and features that we did not get a chance to explore earlier</li>
    <li>Iterate and improve the areas of concern listed above</li>
    <li>Test again later with users</li>
    <li>Continue to explore competitor offerings and shortfalls</li>
    <li>Shape a minimal feature list for the initial launch</li>
    <li>Define and refine customer personas that are specific to target markets to help shape the MVP further</li>
  </ul>

